\begin_layout Subsection*
The Ansatz (Law of mass action)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is formulated in terms of the law of mass action (LMA), i.e.,
 as system of ordinary differential equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Let there be 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 particle species.
 The concentration of them at a fixed time is given by a vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bm{x}(t)=\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}(t)\\
\vdots\\
x_{S}(t)
\end{pmatrix}\in\mathbb{R}^{S}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Further, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 reactions, represented by rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and a reaction function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta_{r}(\bm{x}(t))=\begin{pmatrix}\theta_{r,1}\\
\vdots\\
\theta_{r,S}
\end{pmatrix}(\bm{x}(t)),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
so that the change of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is represented by the ordinary differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}_{i}(t)=\sum_{r=1}^{R}\theta_{r,i}(\bm{x}(t))\xi_{r}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\series bold
Example: 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B\to C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\to A$
\end_inset

 be given reactions with macroscopic rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, then the representing system of ordinary differential equations
 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\bm{x}}(t)=\begin{pmatrix}\dot{x}_{A}(t)\\
\dot{x}_{B}(t)\\
\dot{x}_{C}(t)
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}-x_{A}(t)x_{B}(t) & x_{C}(t)\\
-x_{A}(t)x_{B}(t) & 0\\
x_{A}(t)x_{B}(t) & -x_{C}(t)
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}\xi_{1}\\
\xi_{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Learn rates from data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{X}\in\mathbb{R}^{T\times S}$
\end_inset

 be a trajectory containing concentrations of particles per time and species
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 time steps.
 Propose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 reactions with corresponding reaction functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{r}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and at this point unknown rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{r}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Application of the trajectory to the LMA yields a data tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta(\bm{X})\in\mathbb{R}^{T\times S\times R}$
\end_inset

 with a corresponding rates vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xi\in\mathbb{R}^{R}$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\bm{X}}=\Theta(\bm{X})\Xi.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Theta(\bm{X})\Xi & = & \sum_{r=1}^{R}\theta_{r}(\bm{X})\xi_{r}\\
 & = & \begin{pmatrix}\theta_{1,1}(\bm{X})\\
\vdots\\
\theta_{1,S}(\bm{X})
\end{pmatrix}\xi_{1}+\ldots+\begin{pmatrix}\theta_{R,1}(\bm{X})\\
\vdots\\
\theta_{R,S}(\bm{X})
\end{pmatrix}\xi_{R},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e., the system of equations is linear in the rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Goal is to find the rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Xi}$
\end_inset

 that minimize the residual in the above equation with respect to the Frobenius
 norm.
 Sparsity in the solution can be enforced by Lasso, i.e., introducing an 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 penalty term with hyperparameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally one can introduce an 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

penalty, i.e.
 Elastic Net, with weighting 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 The problem reads: Find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\Xi}=\text{argmin}_{\Xi}(\frac{1}{2T}\|\dot{\bm{X}}-\Theta(\bm{X})\Xi\|_{F}^{2}+\alpha\lambda\|\Xi\|_{1}+\alpha(1-\lambda)\|\Xi\|_{2})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xi_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be noted that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 the problem reduces to Lasso and for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 the problem reduces to Ridge regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Implementation / solving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let a trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{X}$
\end_inset

 be given as output from, e.g., the Gillespie method.
 The time derivative is computed by linearly interpolating 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{X}$
\end_inset

 between each two changes in concentration and then calculating the gradient
 on these non-uniform data points:
\end_layout

