\begin_layout Standard
Theta can also be computed as well as an analytical derivative of the objective
 function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\bm{X}) & =\frac{1}{2T}\|\dot{\bm{X}}-\Theta(\bm{X})\Xi\|_{F}^{2}+\alpha\lambda\|\Xi\|_{1}+\alpha(1-\lambda)\|\Xi\|_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimization problem is solved using sequential least squares (SLSQP)
 from scipy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let reactions 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\to A$
\end_inset

 with rates 
\begin_inset Formula $4.0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

, respectively, be given.
 Data was generated by the Gillespie method and then sampling the yielded
 concentration for each species with a fixed step size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, resulting in a corresponding trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The time derivative was computed by linearly interpolating 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{X}$
\end_inset

 between each two changes of concentration and then calculating the gradient.
 (This causes a rather oscillatory derivative, however trying to smooth
 it yielded wrong rates in this case).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimization problem was then evaluated for a choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

, i.e., as a constrained regression problem.
\end_layout

